        "content": "<p>In the last few years, I've developed a certain idea/opinion/bias that may be worth putting out there and having challenged by the community at large. In my view, a good way to motivate adjunctions is through the concept of duality, which permeates our way of thinking about mathematical objects (from very basic ones, like the relationship between closed and open sets, to higher level abstractions, like scheme theory). </p>\n<p>Let me point out that whether contravariant equivalences are sufficient to encode dualities in general is debatable, as there are counterexamples to such an idea, for example Isbell duality.  So, my claim is that adjunctions are associated with a \"relaxed\" version of duality (or, perhaps, the right version of it). This leads me to believe that the centrality of adjunctions in mathematics may stem from the fact that they embody a form of duality that \"makes more sense\": strong enough to be useful and meaningful in many contexts, yet weak enough to be flexible and widely applicable.</p>\n<p>In particular, I feel that duality deserves more attention when motivating adjunctions in mathematical discussions, especially since it is more familiar and intuitive for those coming from outside category theory.</p>",
        "id": 519588007,
        "sender_full_name": "Antonio Lorenzin",
        "timestamp": 1747827159
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In line with Urs Schreiber's thinking, e.g., <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/schreiber/show/Per%C3%AC+Panthe%C5%8Dr%C3%ADas\">here</a>:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/kNvaEE3ynJpbtRzHsmu7e1uj/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/kNvaEE3ynJpbtRzHsmu7e1uj/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"700x359\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/kNvaEE3ynJpbtRzHsmu7e1uj/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 519591710,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1747828286
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's an article of mine you might enjoy:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>2017, <em>Duality as a category-theoretic concept</em>, Studies in History and Philosophy of Modern Physics, Volume 59, August 2017, Pages 55-61, (<a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/davidcorfield/files/duality.pdf\">pdf</a>)</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 519592419,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1747828449
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Lambek had a more specific view, that you could think of Adjunctions as \"an amusing analogy\" for the unity of opposites. He talked about this in his paper <a href=\"https://www.researchgate.net/file.PostFileLoader.html?id=53ac5970d685ccdf2b8b465f&amp;assetKey=AS%3A273549233721345%401442230627468\">\"The influence of Heraclitus on modern mathematics\"</a>, as well as noting that Lawvere saw an opportunity to make this philosophical idea fully precise. </p>\n<p>Lawvere's approach for modeling unity of opposites involves three functors with two adjunctions(a nice stack exchange answer on this: <a href=\"https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/2357569/can-you-explain-lawveres-work-on-hegel-to-someone-who-knows-basic-category-theo\">https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/2357569/can-you-explain-lawveres-work-on-hegel-to-someone-who-knows-basic-category-theo</a>)</p>\n<p>Lambek was fine with just one adjunction.</p>\n<p>I don't know enough philosophy to speak on the relative merits of their approaches.</p>",
        "id": 519626394,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1747837468
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277352\">Alex Kreitzberg</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229134-theory.3A-philosophy/topic/adjunctions.20and.20dualities/near/519626394\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Lawvere's approach for modeling unity of opposites involves three functors with two adjunctions</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The nLab talks about that at <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/adjoint+modality\">[[adjoint modality]]</a>.</p>\n<p>Of course, an <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/adjoint+triple\">[[adjoint triple]]</a> is a kind of adjunction of adjunctions:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/ttU5xYPxVbvyA8hpHDUw0cPU/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/ttU5xYPxVbvyA8hpHDUw0cPU/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"681x74\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/ttU5xYPxVbvyA8hpHDUw0cPU/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div>",
        "id": 519636372,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1747839785
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I struggle with the \"primordial ooze\" of category theory. After the tenth \"A this is just a that\" I stopped trying to explain things in terms of other things and just try to keep track of mental pictures for each widget. </p>\n<p>But that feels somehow like the opposite of what you're supposed to do in category theory <span aria-label=\"laughing\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f606\" role=\"img\" title=\"laughing\">:laughing:</span>.</p>\n<p>Maybe there's an adjunction between understanding just one thing and understanding everything related to one thing. (As I say that as a joke I immediately wonder \"is that a, too weak, statement of the yoneda lemma?\" This subject never lets me relax!)</p>",
        "id": 519643485,
        "sender_full_name": "Alex Kreitzberg",
        "timestamp": 1747841495
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>After the tenth \"A this is just a that\" I stopped trying to explain things in terms of other things and just try to keep track of mental pictures for each widget.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think it's good to develop a mental image of each widget and use these to <em>see</em> why various \"a this is just a that\" facts are true.   For example I can see why a monoid object in the bicategory of spans of sets is just... a category!  At first this seemed like a very 'abstract' and scary fact, which was easy to forget, but now I can just see it.    </p>\n<p>(I'm using visual metaphors for understanding because I do in fact have a mental image of what's going on here, but verbal, non-visual understanding is also powerful and can be better.)</p>",
        "id": 519676559,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1747852126
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm curious whether the mental image is an image <em>of a span</em>, eg of the actual glyphs <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>O</mi><mo>←</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>O</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">O\\leftarrow M\\to O</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">O</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">←</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">O</span></span></span></span> as you'd write them out to check this result, or an image of some particular elements of this span.</p>",
        "id": 519682457,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1747854188
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The notation <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>O</mi><mo>←</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>O</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">O \\leftarrow M \\rightarrow O</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">O</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">←</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">O</span></span></span></span> is a nice instance of the microcosm principle, since if these are sets I see each one as a bag of dots, and each dot in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> gets mapped to two dots in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">O</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">O</span></span></span></span> thus:</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>∙</mo><mo>←</mo><mo>∙</mo><mo>→</mo><mo>∙</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\bullet \\leftarrow \\bullet \\rightarrow \\bullet</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4445em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∙</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">←</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4445em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∙</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4445em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∙</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>though in my imagery it's important that those arrows point diagonally down.</p>",
        "id": 519693304,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1747858117
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"302507\">David Corfield</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229134-theory.3A-philosophy/topic/adjunctions.20and.20dualities/near/519636372\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277352\">Alex Kreitzberg</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229134-theory.3A-philosophy/topic/adjunctions.20and.20dualities/near/519626394\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Lawvere's approach for modeling unity of opposites involves three functors with two adjunctions</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The nLab talks about that at <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/adjoint+modality\">[[adjoint modality]]</a>.</p>\n<p>Of course, an <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/adjoint+triple\">[[adjoint triple]]</a> is a kind of adjunction of adjunctions:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/ttU5xYPxVbvyA8hpHDUw0cPU/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>is the opposite true? is any adjunction of adjunctions of that form?</p>",
        "id": 520599470,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1748331357
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, in the sense that there's an equivalence:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/_znvyKpEO7Qisf7y50ADJMu7/image.png\">image.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/_znvyKpEO7Qisf7y50ADJMu7/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img data-original-content-type=\"image/png\" data-original-dimensions=\"690x80\" src=\"/user_uploads/thumbnail/21317/_znvyKpEO7Qisf7y50ADJMu7/image.png/840x560.webp\"></a></div><p>Oh, was the question whether there are cases of</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>⊣</mo><mi>G</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>⊣</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>J</mi><mo>⊣</mo><mi>H</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> (F \\dashv G) \\dashv (J \\dashv H)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09618em;\">J</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>J</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">J</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09618em;\">J</span></span></span></span> distinct?</p>",
        "id": 520628216,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1748339970
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>exactly!</p>",
